@Victor

The website you linked has an extreme aversion to the word LEPER, but uses the term "leprosy" prolifically.  Plus, the organization is actually called The Leprosy Mission, and the site doesn't even mention "Hansen's disease."  Do they really think that calling these victims "people affected by leprosy" instead of "lepers" fools anyone?

The Biblical context disallows the use of "Hansen's disease," and I'm sure the clue was written that way to avoid any connection to modern-day Hansen's victims.

@Victor

I find virtue signaling offensive.  So do a lot of other people. 

Whatcha gonna do about it?

@Steve L

So, it’s silly of people with a disease to be  upset about being called a name that reduces their identity to just that disease? I never thought about it before, but it makes perfect sense to me. Would someone with diabetes like being called a diabeter?

Why are some people so easily offended by new information?

@The X-Phile

